{"title_page": "Boom Technology", "text_new": "{{short description|American startup aircraft company}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name          = Boom Technology, Inc\n|logo          = Boom Technology logo (black).svg\n|image         = \n|image_caption =  \n|type          = [[Private company|Private]]\n|industry      = [[Aerospace industry]]\n|key_people    =\n{{plainlist|\n*Blake Scholl <small>([[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]])</small>\n*Joe Wilding <small>(Chief Engineer)</small>\n*Josh Krall <small>([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])</small>\n|}}\n|products      = [[Supersonic aircraft]] design\n|revenue       = \n|num_employees = \n|parent        = \n|founders      = Blake Scholl<br>Joe Wilding<br>Josh Krall\n|slogan        =\n|foundation    = {{start date and age|2014}}<br>[[Denver]], [[Colorado]], U.S.\n|location      = [[Centennial Airport]], [[Dove Valley, Colorado]]\n|homepage      = {{url|https://boomsupersonic.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Boom Technology''' is an American [[startup company]] designing a {{cvt|2.2|Mach|60,000|kn km/h|-2}} 55-passenger [[supersonic transport]] with a range of {{cvt|4,500|nmi|km}}, to be introduced in 2023, called the [[Boom Overture|Overture]].\n<!--History-->\nAfter being [[Business incubator|incubated]] by [[Y Combinator]] in 2016, it raised $51 million of [[venture capital]] in 2017, and a further $100 million by January 2019.\n<!--XB-1 \"Baby Boom\"-->\nThe [[Boom XB-1 Baby Boom]] one-third-scale demonstrator is expected to begin flight testing in 2020.<ref name=Flight19jun2019/>\n\n==History==\n\nThe company was founded in [[Denver]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-21/this-aerospace-company-wants-to-bring-supersonic-civilian-travel-back |date=21 March 2016 |url-access= subscription |title=This Aerospace Company Wants to Bring Supersonic Civilian Travel Back |first=Ashlee |last=Vance |agency= Bloomberg}}</ref>\nIt participated in a [[Y Combinator]] startup [[List of Y-Combinator Startups#Winter 2016|incubation program]] in early 2016, and has been funded by Y Combinator, [[Sam Altman]], Seraph Group, [[Eight Partners]], and others.<ref name=Fortune2016March>{{cite news |url= http://fortune.com/2016/03/23/boom-supersonic-virgin-deal/ |date= 23 March 2016 |title= This Startup Is Developing Supersonic Planes for Virgin Group |first=Kia |last=Kokalitcheva |publisher=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, $33 million were invested by several [[venture fund]]s: Continuity Fund, RRE Ventures, Palm Drive Ventures, 8VC and Caffeinated Capital.<ref name=Flight5dec2017>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-jal-invests-heavily-in-supersonic-boom-443857/ |title= JAL invests heavily in supersonic Boom |date= 5 Dec 2017 |author= Stephen Trimble |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\nBoom secured $41 million of total financing by April 2017.<ref name=ATW170503>{{cite news |url= http://atwonline.com/technology/boom-ceo-sees-market-1000-supersonic-passenger-jets-2035 |title= Boom CEO sees market for 1,000 supersonic passenger jets by 2035 |date= May 3, 2017 |author= Aaron Karp |work= Air Transport World |publisher= Aviation Week }}</ref>\nIn December 2017, [[Japan Airlines]] invested $10 million, raising the company capital to $51 million: enough to build the XB-1 \u201cBaby Boom\u201d demonstrator and complete its testing, and to start early design work on the 55-seat airliner.<ref name=Flight5dec2017/> In January 2019, Boom raised a further $100 million, bringing the total to $151 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeremybogaisky/2019/01/04/boom-raises-100m-to-develop-supersonic-jet-its-going-to-need-a-lot-more/|title=Boom Raises $100M To Develop A Supersonic Airliner. It's Going To Need A Whole Lot More.|last=Bogaisky|first=Jeremy|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref>  With this new financing, the first test flight of the demonstrator aircraft was planned for later in 2019.<ref>[https://www.prweb.com/releases/boom_supersonic_closes_100_million_series_b_to_develop_overture_its_revolutionary_mach_2_2_airliner/prweb16012481.htm Boom Supersonic Closes 100 Million Series B to Develop Overture, its Revolutionary Mach-2.2 Airliner (PR Web, January 2019)]</ref>\n\n==XB-1 Baby Boom==\n{{Main|Boom XB-1 Baby Boom}}\nThe XB-1 Baby Boom is a one-third-scale supersonic demonstrator, designed to maintain Mach 2.2, with over {{cvt|1000|nmi|km}} of range, and powered by three {{cvt|4,300|lbf|kN}} dry [[General Electric CJ610]]s.<ref name=AvWeek10Jul2018>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/propulsion/boom-focuses-derivative-engines-supersonic-airliner-plan |title= Boom Focuses On Derivative Engines For Supersonic Airliner Plan |date= Jul 10, 2018 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>\nIt is expected to be flight tested in 2020.<ref name=Flight19jun2019>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/paris-boom-xb-1-schedule-slips-while-jal-eyes-ove-459129/ |title= Boom XB-1 schedule slips, while JAL eyes Overture |date= 19 June 2019 |author= Greg Waldron |work= flightglobal}}</ref> A simulator for the XB-1 has been constructed using [[X-Plane (simulator)|X-Plane]] 11 to test the flight model.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boomsupersonic.com/xb-1|title=Boom - XB-1|website=boomsupersonic.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==Overture airliner==\n{{Main|Boom Overture}}\n\nThe Overture is a proposed {{cvt|2.2|Mach|60,000|kn km/h|-2}}, 55-passenger [[supersonic transport]] with {{cvt|4,500|nmi|km}} of range,<ref name=ATW170503>{{cite news |url= http://atwonline.com/technology/boom-ceo-sees-market-1000-supersonic-passenger-jets-2035 |title= Boom CEO sees market for 1,000 supersonic passenger jets by 2035 |date= May 3, 2017 |author= Aaron Karp |work= Air Transport World |publisher= Aviation Week }}</ref> to be introduced in 2025.<ref name=AIN18Jul2018>{{cite news |url= https://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/air-transport/2018-07-18/supersonic-future-remains-uncertain-says-new-report |title= Supersonic Future Remains Uncertain, Says New Report |author= Mark Phelps |date= July 18, 2018 |work= AIN online}}</ref>\nWith 500 viable routes, there could be a market for 1,000 supersonic airliners with [[business class]] fares.<ref name=ATW170503/> It had gathered 76 commitments by December 2017.<ref name=Flight5dec2017>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-jal-invests-heavily-in-supersonic-boom-443857/ |title= JAL invests heavily in supersonic Boom |date= 5 Dec 2017 |author= Stephen Trimble |work= Flightglobal}}</ref> It would keep the [[delta wing]] configuration of [[Concorde]]<ref name=Leeham17nov2016>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2016/11/17/will-boom-succeed-concorde-failed/ |title= Will Boom succeed where Concorde failed? |work= Leeham News |author= Bjorn Fehrm |date= November 17, 2016}}</ref> but would be built with [[composite materials]].<ref name=Flight5dec2017/> It would be powered by [[trijet|three]] dry {{cvt|15,000|-|20,000|lbf|kN}} [[turbofans]];<ref name=Flight5dec2017/> a derivative or a clean-sheet design will be selected in 2019.<ref name=AvWeek23jan2019>{{cite news |url =http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/boom-advances-overture-supersonic-airliner-demonstrator-takes-shape |title= Boom Advances Overture Supersonic Airliner As Demonstrator Takes Shape |date= Jan 23, 2019 |author= Graham Warwick |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent\n|see also=\n* [[Supersonic business jet]]\n* [[Aerion]]\n* [[Spike S-512]]\n|similar aircraft=\n|lists=\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://boomsupersonic.com/}}\n\n{{Supersonic transport}}\n\n[[Category:Aircraft manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Denver]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Aerospace companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established in 2014]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American startup aircraft company}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name          = Boom Technology, Inc\n|logo          = Boom Technology logo (black).svg\n|image         = \n|image_caption =  \n|type          = [[Private company|Private]]\n|industry      = [[Aerospace industry]]\n|key_people    =\n{{plainlist|\n*Blake Scholl <small>([[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]])</small>\n*Joe Wilding <small>(Chief Engineer)</small>\n*Josh Krall <small>([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])</small>\n|}}\n|products      = [[Supersonic aircraft]] design\n|revenue       = \n|num_employees = \n|parent        = \n|founders      = Blake Scholl<br>Joe Wilding<br>Josh Krall\n|slogan        =\n|foundation    = {{start date and age|2014}}<br>[[Denver]], [[Colorado]], U.S.\n|location      = [[Centennial Airport]], [[Dove Valley, Colorado]]\n|homepage      = {{url|https://boomsupersonic.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Boom Technology''' is an American [[startup company]] designing a {{cvt|2.2|Mach|60,000|kn km/h|-2}} 55-passenger [[supersonic transport]] with a range of {{cvt|4,500|nmi|km}}, to be introduced in 2023, called the [[Boom Overture|Overture]].\n<!--History-->\nAfter being [[Business incubator|incubated]] by [[Y Combinator]] in 2016, it raised $51 million of [[venture capital]] in 2017, and a further $100 million by January 2019.\n<!--XB-1 \"Baby Boom\"-->\nThe [[Boom XB-1 Baby Boom]] one-third-scale demonstrator is expected to begin flight testing in 2020.<ref name=Flight19jun2019/>\n\n==History==\n\nThe company was founded in [[Denver]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-21/this-aerospace-company-wants-to-bring-supersonic-civilian-travel-back |date=21 March 2016 |url-access= subscription |title=This Aerospace Company Wants to Bring Supersonic Civilian Travel Back |first=Ashlee |last=Vance |agency= Bloomberg}}</ref>\nIt participated in a [[Y Combinator]] startup [[List of Y-Combinator Startups#Winter 2016|incubation program]] in early 2016, and has been funded by Y Combinator, [[Sam Altman]], Seraph Group, [[Eight Partners]], and others.<ref name=Fortune2016March>{{cite news |url= http://fortune.com/2016/03/23/boom-supersonic-virgin-deal/ |date= 23 March 2016 |title= This Startup Is Developing Supersonic Planes for Virgin Group |first=Kia |last=Kokalitcheva |publisher=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, $33 million were invested by several [[venture fund]]s: Continuity Fund, RRE Ventures, Palm Drive Ventures, 8VC and Caffeinated Capital.<ref name=Flight5dec2017>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-jal-invests-heavily-in-supersonic-boom-443857/ |title= JAL invests heavily in supersonic Boom |date= 5 Dec 2017 |author= Stephen Trimble |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\nBoom secured $41 million of total financing by April 2017.<ref name=ATW170503>{{cite news |url= http://atwonline.com/technology/boom-ceo-sees-market-1000-supersonic-passenger-jets-2035 |title= Boom CEO sees market for 1,000 supersonic passenger jets by 2035 |date= May 3, 2017 |author= Aaron Karp |work= Air Transport World |publisher= Aviation Week }}</ref>\nIn December 2017, [[Japan Airlines]] invested $10 million, raising the company capital to $51 million: enough to build the XB-1 \u201cBaby Boom\u201d demonstrator and complete its testing, and to start early design work on the 55-seat airliner.<ref name=Flight5dec2017/> In January 2019, Boom raised a further $100 million, bringing the total to $151 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeremybogaisky/2019/01/04/boom-raises-100m-to-develop-supersonic-jet-its-going-to-need-a-lot-more/|title=Boom Raises $100M To Develop A Supersonic Airliner. It's Going To Need A Whole Lot More.|last=Bogaisky|first=Jeremy|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref>  With this new financing, the first test flight of the demonstrator aircraft was planned for later in 2019.<ref>[https://www.prweb.com/releases/boom_supersonic_closes_100_million_series_b_to_develop_overture_its_revolutionary_mach_2_2_airliner/prweb16012481.htm Boom Supersonic Closes 100 Million Series B to Develop Overture, its Revolutionary Mach-2.2 Airliner (PR Web, January 2019)]</ref>\n\n==XB-1 Baby Boom==\n{{Main|Boom XB-1 Baby Boom}}\nThe XB-1 Baby Boom is a one-third-scale supersonic demonstrator, designed to maintain Mach 2.2, with over {{cvt|1000|nmi|km}} of range, and powered by three {{cvt|4,300|lbf|kN}} dry [[General Electric CJ610]]s.<ref name=AvWeek10Jul2018>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/propulsion/boom-focuses-derivative-engines-supersonic-airliner-plan |title= Boom Focuses On Derivative Engines For Supersonic Airliner Plan |date= Jul 10, 2018 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>\nIt is expected to be flight tested in 2020.<ref name=Flight19jun2019>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/paris-boom-xb-1-schedule-slips-while-jal-eyes-ove-459129/ |title= Boom XB-1 schedule slips, while JAL eyes Overture |date= 19 June 2019 |author= Greg Waldron |work= flightglobal}}</ref> A simulator for the XB-1 has been constructed using X-Plane 11 to test the flight model.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boomsupersonic.com/xb-1|title=Boom - XB-1|website=boomsupersonic.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==Overture airliner==\n{{Main|Boom Overture}}\n\nThe Overture is a proposed {{cvt|2.2|Mach|60,000|kn km/h|-2}}, 55-passenger [[supersonic transport]] with {{cvt|4,500|nmi|km}} of range,<ref name=ATW170503>{{cite news |url= http://atwonline.com/technology/boom-ceo-sees-market-1000-supersonic-passenger-jets-2035 |title= Boom CEO sees market for 1,000 supersonic passenger jets by 2035 |date= May 3, 2017 |author= Aaron Karp |work= Air Transport World |publisher= Aviation Week }}</ref> to be introduced in 2025.<ref name=AIN18Jul2018>{{cite news |url= https://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/air-transport/2018-07-18/supersonic-future-remains-uncertain-says-new-report |title= Supersonic Future Remains Uncertain, Says New Report |author= Mark Phelps |date= July 18, 2018 |work= AIN online}}</ref>\nWith 500 viable routes, there could be a market for 1,000 supersonic airliners with [[business class]] fares.<ref name=ATW170503/> It had gathered 76 commitments by December 2017.<ref name=Flight5dec2017>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-jal-invests-heavily-in-supersonic-boom-443857/ |title= JAL invests heavily in supersonic Boom |date= 5 Dec 2017 |author= Stephen Trimble |work= Flightglobal}}</ref> It would keep the [[delta wing]] configuration of [[Concorde]]<ref name=Leeham17nov2016>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2016/11/17/will-boom-succeed-concorde-failed/ |title= Will Boom succeed where Concorde failed? |work= Leeham News |author= Bjorn Fehrm |date= November 17, 2016}}</ref> but would be built with [[composite materials]].<ref name=Flight5dec2017/> It would be powered by [[trijet|three]] dry {{cvt|15,000|-|20,000|lbf|kN}} [[turbofans]];<ref name=Flight5dec2017/> a derivative or a clean-sheet design will be selected in 2019.<ref name=AvWeek23jan2019>{{cite news |url =http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/boom-advances-overture-supersonic-airliner-demonstrator-takes-shape |title= Boom Advances Overture Supersonic Airliner As Demonstrator Takes Shape |date= Jan 23, 2019 |author= Graham Warwick |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent\n|see also=\n* [[Supersonic business jet]]\n* [[Aerion]]\n* [[Spike S-512]]\n|similar aircraft=\n|lists=\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://boomsupersonic.com/}}\n\n{{Supersonic transport}}\n\n[[Category:Aircraft manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:American compani